`this.state.rssreads.map(rssreads =&gt; {` this is the line you are talking ***about!!!

**Undefined**. Even though you set it in the constructor to an empty array &#160;[]. That can mean but only one thing. You are screwing it somewhere. In such a situation the fastest way to find the culprit is to &lt;kbd&gt;CTRL&lt;/kbd&gt;+&lt;kbd&gt;f&lt;/kbd&gt; and search for **setState**.

You&#39;ll find the culprit quickly.

But what can be the problem !!! Bad setting of the state. setting only one  without the rest! React **setState()** method **expect the hole state each time** !!

for instance in your code 
```javascript 
handlePageChange(pageNumber) {
    console.log(`active page is ${pageNumber}`);
    this.setState({activePage: pageNumber}); // &lt;------ that&#39;s a mistake !!!!!!!!!!

    axios.get(&#39;/view?page=&#39; + pageNumber).then(response =&gt; {
        this.setState({
            rssreads: response.data.data,
            itemsCountPerPage: response.data.per_page,
            totalItemsCount: response.data.total,
            activePage: response.data.current_page,


        });

    });
}

```

**You should do it this way :**

```javascript
  this.setState({...this.state, activePage: pageNumber});
```

**copy all the state and override only the one property.**

**But what if i want to reset all the state including for example in your code the rssreads !!!!**

```javascript
  this.setState({activePage: pageNumber, rssreads: []}); 

```
That if the the rest are ok to be undefined!! (and You reset the properties one by one !!!!!)

**If the rest must keep there values :**
```javascript
  this.setState({...this.state, activePage: pageNumber, rssreads: []}); 

```

**And lastly what if there is many properties and i don&#39;t want to go through them all one by one or something.** 

**The answer to that :** would be build a function that allow you to create the new state easily. You can think about it. As it will be nice. But well for practice there is libraries for that. And the best that i like is **immer** here it is. So check it out. 

https://www.npmjs.com/package/immer 

Here an example:

```javascript
import immerProduce from &#39;immer&#39;;

store.dispatch(setGlobalStates(
    immerProduce(globalStates, (draft) =&gt; {
	    draft.loadingSpinner.show = true;
	})
));
```

I&#39;m using it within redux. But the important thing, is that the action creator (or just method) `setGlobalStates` is expecting the new state!
With **immer**. You pass the old state here `globalStates`. And then you have the callback and draft that represent the current state. You make the changes in a normal way. mutating normally (in a mutative manner). Then **immer** will figure it out and return the new immutable state. Cool. No hassle and simple.
You use that when you need it. Not always you&#39;ll need that.

And lately sometimes the culprit is just in the fetching process itself. When you get the data you don&#39;t get it well. So always you have to doubt and check in the end of course if nothing work !!!!!!

And you can always use things like:
```javascript
myVar || defaultValue // if the first undefined the second will take place

myCondition ? thisV: orthis

myList ||&#160;[]

// or simply conditions
thisV &amp;&amp; thisB &amp;&amp; thisL // if the first is true it evaluate the next one. if true too it will return the last. If one is false the whole thing is false!

if () {} else {}


// in expression and variable binding  you can even do that!

&lt;div&gt;{
(() =&gt; {   // &lt;-------------------- an IIFE (Immediately Invoked Function Expression)
    // my cool processing
    return whatToReturn;
})()
}&lt;/div&gt;

```

# spread operator
```javascript
    this.setState({ 
        ...this.state, 
        rssreads: myData || [], 
        otherProp: oneAfterAnotherButOnlyTheOneThatYouNeedToReset,
        //......
    );
```
`...` is the spread operator. In that usage it allow easy merge! 

So you are saying grab all the old state, and override or add this and that !


The Equivalent is 
```javascript
Object.assign({}, this.state, {rssreads: myData, ..}); 
```

ref: 

- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Spread_syntax

- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Object/assign


And a note `myData || []`. Mean if the first is a truthy value take it. If it is not and a falsy value use the second! So if myData is undefined then [] will be used. The equiv of `myData || []` is `myData ? myData : []`.


This way the answer is more complete.

